WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.420
Hi, very excited to be here.

00:00:08.420 --> 00:00:15.480
So I do a lot of exploratory data analysis and a lot of that flow is built around reading

00:00:15.480 --> 00:00:17.440
data into memory.

00:00:17.440 --> 00:00:24.080
The first step is we import some data before we can transform, visualize, model it, and

00:00:24.080 --> 00:00:28.280
if you're in this room, it might be because this database is track, it might be because

00:00:28.280 --> 00:00:32.119
a lot of the time that's not where the data we need is.

00:00:32.119 --> 00:00:38.080
In a lot of organizations, we work with data that's in a database, MySQL, Postgres, Snowflake,

00:00:38.080 --> 00:00:44.000
SQL Server, and a lot of those exciting data analyses don't start from reading a CSV into

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:45.000
memory.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:48.000
They start by hitting data that's in SQL.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:53.080
I have a strong belief that working with a database should be as easy for your team as

00:00:53.080 --> 00:00:54.080
possible.

00:00:54.439 --> 00:00:58.720
Last couple of years, there's been a lot of attention to how can we build R packages that

00:00:58.720 --> 00:01:04.919
make working within a company really smooth, that really help people get to the data that

00:01:04.919 --> 00:01:12.699
matters for the team, and that first kind of really hit me when I was in my first data

00:01:12.699 --> 00:01:15.760
scientist role at Stack Overflow.

00:01:15.760 --> 00:01:22.320
So when I first got in there, I was the first R user, and I ended up building an internal

00:01:22.559 --> 00:01:31.120
package called SQL Stack R that managed connecting and working with the data in those databases.

00:01:31.120 --> 00:01:36.400
Every job I've had since, I've built some similar iteration onto that same template

00:01:36.400 --> 00:01:42.320
of creating a package that wraps a database connection.

00:01:42.320 --> 00:01:46.480
So now we've open sourced it as DB Cooper.

00:01:46.480 --> 00:01:53.519
So DB Cooper started as an R package named after the famous bandit, the hijacker, DB

00:01:53.519 --> 00:01:54.519
Cooper.

00:01:54.519 --> 00:01:58.400
And I'm excited to share that while it started as an R package, Michael Chow has actually

00:01:58.400 --> 00:02:04.199
ported it to Python, so now there's both a DB Cooper R and Python version.

00:02:04.199 --> 00:02:12.440
And what they do is make it one step to create a database-specific packages.

00:02:12.440 --> 00:02:16.759
So if you're at a company, Widgets Inc., you can use DB Cooper to create an internal

00:02:16.759 --> 00:02:24.279
package like Widget R or Widget Pi to help analysts fluidly access the data in your databases.

00:02:24.279 --> 00:02:29.080
Let's talk about the problem that it's solving.

00:02:29.080 --> 00:02:32.360
Mostly today I'm going to be talking from the perspective of the R package, but a lot

00:02:32.360 --> 00:02:37.679
of these same problems and solutions exist in the Python version.

00:02:37.679 --> 00:02:44.119
So what's it like to work with a database from R?

00:02:44.119 --> 00:02:48.279
What might you need to do when you're analyzing data in a database?

00:02:48.279 --> 00:02:52.679
Some common tasks, you might need to list the tables that are in the database, you might

00:02:52.679 --> 00:02:56.360
want to transform tables using dplyr.

00:02:56.360 --> 00:03:00.720
So dbplyr is a really powerful package that lets you work with a remote table, kind of

00:03:00.720 --> 00:03:06.639
as if it were an in-memory table, and who here has used dbplyr?

00:03:06.639 --> 00:03:08.720
It is a really fun experience, isn't it?

00:03:08.720 --> 00:03:13.979
We sometimes can't just use dbplyr, we want to run our custom SQL queries.

00:03:13.979 --> 00:03:18.639
So we want to construct SQL, select statements ourselves and try running them.

00:03:18.639 --> 00:03:26.320
And sometimes we need to execute a command, like creating a table or dropping a table.

00:03:26.320 --> 00:03:30.779
So I'll give an example here of how we might work with a SQL connection.

00:03:30.779 --> 00:03:37.020
So this is a database called Lamin, it's based on the Lamin baseball statistics dataset,

00:03:37.020 --> 00:03:41.740
a really phenomenal collection of tables, and it comes built into dbplyr.

00:03:41.740 --> 00:03:46.740
So we've got this Lamin db object, it's a SQL connection.

00:03:46.740 --> 00:03:52.860
And let's start with how might we go about listing tables?

00:03:52.860 --> 00:03:58.419
We use the db list tables function from DBI, would get us a vector of the tables in the

00:03:58.419 --> 00:03:59.419
database.

00:03:59.419 --> 00:04:06.619
If we wanted to work with a remote table as if it were a dbplyr table, we'd use the tbl

00:04:06.619 --> 00:04:07.619
function.

00:04:07.619 --> 00:04:10.940
Tbl on this database, we want to get one of the tables out of it.

00:04:10.940 --> 00:04:15.820
In the case of the Lamin data, I might be interested in its table on batting statistics.

00:04:15.820 --> 00:04:21.940
If I want to run a SQL query, I'd still use the tbl function, but now I could use the

00:04:21.940 --> 00:04:24.899
SQL function to actually construct that query.

00:04:24.899 --> 00:04:29.260
So here I might be writing a query where I'm counting the batting table grouped by

00:04:29.260 --> 00:04:34.299
player ID and getting back some results from it.

00:04:34.299 --> 00:04:42.220
And if I want to execute a command, I might use the db execute function.

00:04:42.220 --> 00:04:51.179
So these four approaches, they work, they do what they're supposed to do, but something

00:04:51.179 --> 00:04:52.959
really bothers me about them.

00:04:52.959 --> 00:04:57.079
Something is just fundamentally a little bit harder to use than I would expect it to be.

00:04:57.079 --> 00:05:01.640
Something is they're not designed how I'd want to work with this data.

00:05:01.640 --> 00:05:08.359
And I really try and figure out what is bothering me about these functions.

00:05:08.359 --> 00:05:12.880
And I'll say, I think that, let's say if I load up this database, what really is bugging

00:05:12.880 --> 00:05:17.480
me is that Lamin db object.

00:05:17.480 --> 00:05:22.799
Like in our environment, we've got this Lamin db object, it's a SQL connection object.

00:05:22.799 --> 00:05:25.440
And I don't know what that is.

00:05:25.440 --> 00:05:27.640
For me, that's the wrong level of abstraction.

00:05:27.640 --> 00:05:30.160
I want to be working with individual tables.

00:05:30.160 --> 00:05:34.839
I want to be directly writing SQL queries and immediately executing them.

00:05:34.839 --> 00:05:38.519
I don't necessarily, I don't know how I'm going to pass this connection around.

00:05:38.519 --> 00:05:44.079
It's a clumsy way to engage with a database.

00:05:44.079 --> 00:05:49.640
So that's why I think there's a missing puzzle piece in between DBI for creating a connection

00:05:49.640 --> 00:05:54.519
to a database, and Dbplyr for transforming and exploring those tables.

00:05:54.519 --> 00:05:58.679
That's where DbCooper comes in.

00:05:58.679 --> 00:06:04.519
It turns a database into an opinionated collection of functions to let us explore it really fluidly,

00:06:04.519 --> 00:06:08.239
kind of as if it were data that were in memory.

00:06:08.239 --> 00:06:13.600
DbCooper takes, you only need to do one function call to set up DbCooper.

00:06:13.600 --> 00:06:14.600
It's DbcInit.

00:06:14.600 --> 00:06:18.519
You pass it the connection object, and you give it a prefix.

00:06:18.519 --> 00:06:22.079
If you've worked with a lot of R packages, you know how useful it can be to have a shared

00:06:22.079 --> 00:06:23.079
prefix.

00:06:23.079 --> 00:06:26.920
DbcInit stores and manages the connection globally.

00:06:26.920 --> 00:06:31.799
It generates a prefixed function for important tasks you would do with that database, and

00:06:31.799 --> 00:06:36.799
really importantly, it generates autocomplete-friendly accessors for tables.

00:06:36.799 --> 00:06:41.119
So I'll show how each of those tasks would be achieved in DbCooper.

00:06:41.119 --> 00:06:47.760
Once you've run DbcInit, instead of doing DbListTables, I would just do lamin underscore

00:06:47.760 --> 00:06:48.760
tbl.

00:06:48.760 --> 00:06:52.079
So that prefix that I passed it turned into a prefix for the function.

00:06:52.079 --> 00:07:06.200
LaminList would return the list of tables that are in the database.

00:07:06.200 --> 00:07:11.160
So lamin, if I want to access just one table, I use lamin underscore tbl.

00:07:11.160 --> 00:07:15.519
So I say lamin tbl, then I can pass it the name of the table, get that one back.

00:07:16.279 --> 00:07:23.200
If I wanted to run a query, I do lamin underscore query and pass the SQL.

00:07:23.200 --> 00:07:25.959
And if I wanted to execute, I'd use lamin underscore execute.

00:07:25.959 --> 00:07:30.279
So one thing to notice about this is it's taking the connection object entirely out

00:07:30.279 --> 00:07:36.040
of the picture, and it's focusing on an opinionated set of tasks that someone might want to do

00:07:36.040 --> 00:07:39.079
with a database.

00:07:39.079 --> 00:07:42.720
My favorite feature about DbCooper is autocomplete.

00:07:43.440 --> 00:07:46.959
So whenever I've worked with a database, it can be hard to remember what the tables are,

00:07:46.959 --> 00:07:52.559
and I get kind of tired of constantly referring back to the documentation or even to a list

00:07:52.559 --> 00:07:55.720
function to see what they are.

00:07:55.720 --> 00:08:01.119
I would maybe run into typos, et cetera, and it just doesn't feel anything like working

00:08:01.119 --> 00:08:03.239
with data that's in memory.

00:08:03.239 --> 00:08:10.600
So DbCooper creates one function for each of the tables in your database so that you

00:08:10.600 --> 00:08:12.559
can access them with autocomplete.

00:08:12.559 --> 00:08:16.239
So it's a much more fluid experience where I can say, if I go into a table, I can just

00:08:16.239 --> 00:08:19.000
start typing it and see, oh, yeah, here are the tables that I'm...

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:22.679
I can't remember exactly what this table in my database is called, but I use autocomplete

00:08:22.679 --> 00:08:23.920
to help me out.

00:08:23.920 --> 00:08:32.200
One thing I like about that is it makes something like a complicated join much more concise

00:08:32.200 --> 00:08:33.799
and much easier to read.

00:08:33.799 --> 00:08:40.080
For me, again, it really means I don't have to remember that I'm working with SQL tables.

00:08:40.080 --> 00:08:49.559
Using DbPlyr with remote tables can feel a lot like using Dplyr with local tables.

00:08:49.559 --> 00:08:52.080
So I've been showing examples of the R function.

00:08:52.080 --> 00:08:57.440
What Michael Chow has set up is really something phenomenal, which is DbCooper.py, where each

00:08:57.440 --> 00:08:58.440
of the...

00:08:58.440 --> 00:09:06.520
It has the same syntax for creating list, table, query, and execute, but it also takes

00:09:06.520 --> 00:09:08.960
advantage of his suba package.

00:09:08.960 --> 00:09:18.719
Suba is a Python port of Dplyr that supports both local pandas data frames and databases.

00:09:18.719 --> 00:09:26.880
So here you can actually see that we could use the lamin data and say .tbl, the salaries,

00:09:26.880 --> 00:09:30.320
and then pipe to count, but all within Python.

00:09:30.320 --> 00:09:35.840
So one thing I think is great about Suba is if you're really familiar with Dplyr and you're

00:09:35.840 --> 00:09:39.119
interested in going over to Python, Suba is absolutely the way to do it.

00:09:39.119 --> 00:09:44.679
And DbCooper in Python is a way to use that in your databases.

00:09:44.679 --> 00:09:50.919
I'm gonna show an example of exploring a database using DbCooper.

00:09:50.919 --> 00:09:56.359
So this is the New York Times COVID-19 database.

00:09:56.359 --> 00:10:04.520
Google makes public a large set of databases of, let's say, 239 databases in Google BigQuery.

00:10:04.520 --> 00:10:09.599
So this is a phenomenal resource, because that means there are 239 packages you could

00:10:09.599 --> 00:10:12.280
write, wrapping each of these data sources.

00:10:12.280 --> 00:10:19.119
I'm gonna show one, which is the New York Times COVID-19 database.

00:10:19.119 --> 00:10:21.280
So we'd start by creating the connection.

00:10:21.280 --> 00:10:23.080
DbCooper doesn't help with this.

00:10:23.080 --> 00:10:27.960
We created ourselves using DbConnect, really whatever approach we would generally use to

00:10:27.960 --> 00:10:30.679
create a database connection.

00:10:30.679 --> 00:10:36.559
And then all we have to do with DbCooper is DbCinit, and we'll say we'll use the prefix

00:10:36.559 --> 00:10:37.559
COVID.

00:10:37.559 --> 00:10:44.179
So all of our functions we're gonna use to access are going to start with the word COVID.

00:10:44.179 --> 00:10:49.479
So now that I have done DbCinit, I could use COVIDLIST, if I wanna say, okay, there are

00:10:49.479 --> 00:10:54.159
four tables in this database.

00:10:54.159 --> 00:10:59.200
And if I wanna access one of them, I could say, okay, COVID underscore US states.

00:10:59.200 --> 00:11:04.039
I've got this autocomplete-friendly way to access one of the tables, and we see data

00:11:04.039 --> 00:11:10.039
that looks like it's a time series that might separate across each of the US states.

00:11:10.039 --> 00:11:13.640
It's got both a column for confirmed cases and deaths.

00:11:13.640 --> 00:11:19.200
My understanding, it gets updated daily, so we could build something on top of this that

00:11:19.200 --> 00:11:23.200
unlike a static data set, it's gonna stay up to date.

00:11:23.200 --> 00:11:27.119
And now that I've got it, I can work with this data as if it were local.

00:11:27.119 --> 00:11:33.799
I can work with it, and I can filter, I can arrange, I can do visualizations.

00:11:33.799 --> 00:11:36.080
So I can, let's say we pipe it through.

00:11:36.080 --> 00:11:40.679
This is actually all this aggregation, this filter, this arrange, this mutate, was all

00:11:40.679 --> 00:11:47.880
turned into a SQL query, gets run, gets brought into memory only when we plot it.

00:11:47.880 --> 00:11:51.159
And this is something that I really like about DbCooper is I just forget I'm using it.

00:11:51.159 --> 00:11:55.640
As soon as you've got these tables, you kind of just go right back into your normal flow.

00:11:55.640 --> 00:12:00.760
I never liked when I worked with SQL databases that I'd have to take one step to do the select

00:12:00.760 --> 00:12:06.440
and the collect, and now I'm working in my traditional exploratory data analysis flow.

00:12:06.440 --> 00:12:11.719
Here you can barely tell where the database ends and where your exploratory data analysis

00:12:11.719 --> 00:12:12.719
begins.

00:12:12.719 --> 00:12:22.799
Where DbCooper really shines is in creating an opinionated package around a database.

00:12:22.799 --> 00:12:23.799
So I'll give an example.

00:12:23.960 --> 00:12:27.840
As I said, I first developed this kind of approach while I was working at Stack Overflow.

00:12:27.840 --> 00:12:33.599
So it's appropriate that we set up a package that wraps a public Stack Overflow database,

00:12:33.599 --> 00:12:42.320
which is one of the BigQuery public databases, is Stack Overflow questions, answers, tags.

00:12:42.320 --> 00:12:49.799
So around this database, we set up the Stack BigQuery package.

00:12:49.799 --> 00:12:53.880
This is a package I put up just as an example of a package that could be created.

00:12:53.880 --> 00:12:55.280
We pick the database.

00:12:55.280 --> 00:12:57.880
Now let's wrap it with a package.

00:12:57.880 --> 00:13:01.400
And the way that we go about doing that is three steps.

00:13:01.400 --> 00:13:04.239
First we write database-specific connection code.

00:13:04.239 --> 00:13:08.400
So anything in terms of setting up credentials, et cetera, that's going to live inside this

00:13:08.400 --> 00:13:13.640
package.

00:13:13.640 --> 00:13:22.400
Then critically, in the .onload and .unload functions, those are functions that run every

00:13:22.400 --> 00:13:29.840
time a package is loaded or unloaded, we're going to create one of those database connections

00:13:29.840 --> 00:13:32.440
and then use DbC init.

00:13:32.440 --> 00:13:37.479
So this means that as soon as somebody loads in this package, it's going to populate the

00:13:37.479 --> 00:13:45.520
package's namespace with functions that start with that prefix stack.

00:13:45.520 --> 00:13:50.159
Now every database is different, and the ways that we explore them are different, too.

00:13:50.159 --> 00:13:55.320
So the next step would be adding database-specific verbs.

00:13:55.320 --> 00:14:00.719
Something that I love to do with Stack Overflow data is look at, say, patterns of trends of

00:14:00.719 --> 00:14:02.080
tags over time.

00:14:02.080 --> 00:14:05.880
I'm really interested in can I aggregate at the tag level?

00:14:05.880 --> 00:14:09.840
That requires joining together a couple tables in the database and doing a little bit of

00:14:09.840 --> 00:14:11.200
custom logic.

00:14:11.200 --> 00:14:16.159
That kind of custom database-specific logic or problem-specific logic or company-specific

00:14:16.159 --> 00:14:21.719
logic is a really good fit for a package that uses DbCooper because it's going to mean that

00:14:21.719 --> 00:14:27.520
when the person using this package actually does this analysis, everything's going to

00:14:27.520 --> 00:14:28.520
be set up for them.

00:14:28.520 --> 00:14:33.719
So when you do library stack BigQuery, now we've got a function stack underscore for

00:14:33.719 --> 00:14:41.119
any of the...we've got stack list, stack table, stack execute, stack query, and one of these

00:14:41.119 --> 00:14:43.359
functions for each of the table accessors.

00:14:43.359 --> 00:14:48.039
So basically by loading library, it's as if every table just got loaded right into their

00:14:48.039 --> 00:14:50.080
environment so they can use it.

00:14:50.080 --> 00:14:53.400
Here's an example of an analysis that I would do.

00:14:53.400 --> 00:14:55.599
Here we go.

00:14:55.599 --> 00:15:02.679
So here's an example of an analysis that I would do, for instance, of tags over time.

00:15:02.679 --> 00:15:07.280
So this is an aggregation that compares a couple of technologies like Python, JavaScript,

00:15:07.280 --> 00:15:13.359
Java, and R in terms of the percentage of stack overflow questions each...it was done

00:15:13.359 --> 00:15:19.559
by month...by month that are tagged with this particular language.

00:15:19.559 --> 00:15:26.280
So we can...notice there's a use of that summarized tags function that's database-specific, and

00:15:26.280 --> 00:15:31.799
then there's just some dplyr, some ggplot2, and again, really quickly, you can forget

00:15:31.799 --> 00:15:38.080
that you're working with a database at all.

00:15:38.080 --> 00:15:42.080
So what I learned from the dbcouper package is kind of really two takeaways.

00:15:42.080 --> 00:15:46.559
One is don't underestimate the value of small usability improvements that affect you every

00:15:46.559 --> 00:15:47.559
day.

00:15:47.559 --> 00:15:54.440
And second is that a good database package lets you forget about the package entirely.

00:15:54.440 --> 00:16:02.679
See, once we've got this data loaded, it's really as if we just had...instead of looking

00:16:02.679 --> 00:16:06.960
at that one connection object, and now we're always working with that connection object,

00:16:06.960 --> 00:16:11.880
now we're just working with all the tables in the database.

00:16:11.880 --> 00:16:17.640
So next time you're working with a database connection, it just takes one line, try dbcouper,

00:16:17.640 --> 00:16:19.760
and I'd love to hear what you think.

00:16:19.760 --> 00:16:20.760
Thank you.

